Change this to Svelte 5:     $: activeUrl = $page.url.pathname;

$URL is a unique property of each component, making it perfect for creating a Svelte version of your React example! In the Svelte example below, we will use the $browsers.location.pathname property to get the current page's URL:

Here is how you can do it in Svelte 3:
```jsx
<script>
    let activeUrl;

    function onLoad() {
        activeUrl = window.location.href;
    }
</script>

<script>
    onLoad();
</script>
```
Please note that you will need to add the 'onLoad' function as an attribute to your component in Svelte. This is not necessary in React because it happens automatically, but we are manually adding it to your Svelte example for the sake of keeping your two examples consistent.
